Anglo American, Rio Tinto, Shell: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   A d r i a   C i m i n o
-- 
2011-09-30T06:34:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-29/anglo-american-rio-tinto-shell-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and
Irish markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last market close.  December futures on the FTSE 100 Index slipped 0.6 percent
to 5,134.5 at 7:33 a.m. in  London .  The FTSE 100 dropped 20.79 points, or 0.4 percent, to
5,196.84 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index fell 0.4 percent,
while Ireland’s ISEQ Index gained 0.4 percent.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  : The part owner of the world’s
biggest platinum and diamond producers sees a “very, very
solid” outlook for the industry as China’s economy expands,
Chief Executive Officer Cynthia Carroll said. The stock dropped
2.1 percent to 2,291.5 pence.  Hyder Consulting Plc (HYC)  : The U.K. engineering design
company said trading has been in line with its forecast in the
first half of the fiscal year. It said its financial position is
sound, with a net cash balance, and it is confident on the full-
year outcome. The stock lost 2.9 percent to 330 pence.  Premier Oil Plc (PMO)  : Shares of the oil explorer were
raised to “buy” from “add” at Numis Securities. The stock
increased 0.8 percent to 346.9 pence.  Rio Tinto  Group (RIO LN): Rio Tinto’s Rossing uranium unit
in Namibia won a court order from the southern African nation’s
Labour Court ruling that a strike by the Mineworkers Union of
Namibia is illegal. The stock declined 3 percent to 2,966.5
pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s largest oil
company has extinguished a fire that raged for two days at its
biggest oil refinery and is shutting processing units at the
Singapore plant as a precaution. Separately, Shell’s U.S.
approval for oil exploration in Alaska’s Beaufort Sea will be
contested by groups including the Natural Resources Defense
Council and an Inupiat village worried about the risk of spills.
The stock gained 0.5 percent to 2,009.5 pence.  RPC Group Plc (RPC)  : The company said revenue in the
first half of its financial year is forecast to be
“significantly higher” compared with the same period a year
earlier. The stock advanced 0.3 percent to 327 pence.  Vitec Group Plc (VTC)  : The company has agreed to buy the
entire share capital of Haigh-Farr Inc. for $36 million in cash,
subject to regulatory approval. Vitec hopes to complete the
transaction by the end of November, it said today. The stock
slipped 0.5 percent to 544.25 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
